# Configuration Guide

## Project Configuration Files

### Next.js Configuration
- File: [next.config.ts](mdc:next.config.ts)
- Purpose: Configures Next.js build settings, environment variables, and plugins
- Key settings: API routes, image optimization, redirects

### TypeScript Configuration
- File: [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json)
- Purpose: TypeScript compiler options and project settings
- Key settings: Path aliases, strict mode, module resolution

### Tailwind Configuration
- File: [tailwind.config.ts](mdc:tailwind.config.ts)
- Purpose: Tailwind CSS customization and theme settings
- Key settings: Colors, spacing, breakpoints, plugins

### ESLint Configuration
- File: [eslint.config.mjs](mdc:eslint.config.mjs)
- Purpose: Code style and quality rules
- Key settings: TypeScript rules, React rules, import rules

### Prettier Configuration
- File: [.prettierrc.js](mdc:.prettierrc.js)
- Purpose: Code formatting rules
- Key settings: Line length, quotes, semicolons

### Environment Configuration
- File: [src/env.ts](mdc:src/env.ts)
- Purpose: Environment variable validation and types
- Key settings: Required variables, type definitions

## Best Practices
1. Keep configuration files in the root directory
2. Use TypeScript for configuration files when possible
3. Document any non-standard configurations
4. Keep sensitive information in environment variables
5. Use consistent formatting across all config files
